<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-621-120  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 621 120.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Canadian Datasystems  June 1990 v22 n6 p12(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bygone common law and copyright. (Canadian law allows seizure andsale of debtor software copyrights) (EDP and the Law) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mersich, Dan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Supreme Court of Ontario rules that a company's softwarecopyright may be seized and sold by a judgement holder.andP;  The saleof copyright allows buyers to reproduce the debtor's software andsell unlimited numbers of copies, while previous law allowed onlythe sale of the debtor's inventory.andP;  The decision is the first toallow seizure and sale of copyright; it contradicts a common lawruling from 1858.andP;  The presiding judge, Justice Francis Carter,said that a mid-19th century judge should not impede thedevelopment of the common law.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CopyrightDebtSoftware PublishersCanadaLegal Issues.andO;Feature:   illustrationcartoon.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>